Q1. What is serialization in Java?
-->Serialization is the process of converting a Java object into a byte stream so that it can be:

    Stored in a file.
    Sent over a network.
    Saved in a database.
    Transferred between applications.
    
    Java performs serialization using the ObjectOutputStream class.
    
    The class whose objects are to be serialized must implement the Serializable interface.
    
    Example
    class Student implements Serializable {
        int id = 101;
        String name = "John";
    }
    ObjectOutputStream oos =
        new ObjectOutputStream(new FileOutputStream("student.dat"));
    
    oos.writeObject(student);
    Interview One-Liner
    
    Serialization is the process of converting a Java object into a byte stream so it can be stored, transferred, or transmitted. 
    It is performed using ObjectOutputStream, and the class must implement the Serializable interface.




Q2. How can you make a class serializable in Java?
-->To make a class serializable, simply implement the Serializable interface.

    Since Serializable is a marker interface, you don't need to implement any methods.
    
    Example
    import java.io.Serializable;
    
    class Student implements Serializable {
        int id;
        String name;
    }
    
    Now objects of the Student class can be serialized using ObjectOutputStream.
    
    Interview One-Liner
    
    A class can be made serializable by implementing the java.io.Serializable marker interface. Since it contains no methods, no implementation
    is required.




Q3. How can you prevent serialization in a subclass when the parent class implements the Serializable interface?
-->Normally, if a parent class implements Serializable, then all its subclasses are automatically serializable.

            There is no way to "unimplement" Serializable in the subclass.
            
            To prevent serialization of the subclass, you can override the serialization process and throw a NotSerializableException.
            
            Example
            import java.io.*;
            
            class Parent implements Serializable { }
            
            class Child extends Parent {
            
                private void writeObject(ObjectOutputStream out) throws IOException {
                    throw new NotSerializableException("Child cannot be serialized");
                }
            }
            Interview One-Liner
            
            A subclass of a serializable parent is automatically serializable. It cannot remove Serializable, but it can prevent serialization by overriding writeObject() and throwing NotSerializableException.







